# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: children-s-acute-transport-service
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] During World War I, air transport was used to provide medical evacuation from front line areas and the battlefield itself.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Fixed wing military air ambulances came into regular use during World War II.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Helicopters became more commonly used for such purposes during the Korean and Vietnam wars.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Later, helicopters were introduced to civilian health care, especially for shorter distances, in and around large cities: transporting paramedics or specialist doctors as needed and transporting patients to hospitals, especially for major trauma cases.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Fixed-wing aircraft remained in use for long-distance medical transport.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air medical services can travel faster and operate in a wider coverage area than a land ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This makes them particularly useful in sparsely populated rural areas.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air medical services have a particular advantage for major trauma injuries.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The controversial theory of the golden hour suggests that major trauma patients should be transported as quickly as possible to a specialist trauma center.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Therefore, medical responders in a helicopter can provide both a higher level of care at the scene of a trauma and faster transport to a trauma center.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] They can also provide critical care when transporting patients from community hospitals to trauma centers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air ambulance transport is expensive, and if utilised poorly is therefore not cost effective.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] When inappropriately deployed to a patient close to a hospital, an air ambulance may add delay to the patient reaching the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In research from 1996, air ambulance services in England and Wales demonstrated no evidence of improvement in vehicle response times (i.e. time from 999 call to an ambulance vehicle being on-scene with the patient) for air ambulance attended patients compared to those attended by a land ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The same review found patient did not arrive at hospital any quicker when attended by an air ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] When the same authors looked at health outcomes in Cornwall and London they found no evidence that the attendance of an air ambulance (HEMS) service improved survival in trauma patients.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Effective use of helicopter services for trauma depends on the ground responder's ability to determine whether the patient's condition warrants air medical transport.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Protocols and training must be developed to ensure appropriate triage criteria are applied.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Excessively stringent criteria can prevent rapid care and transport of trauma victims; relaxed criteria can result in the patient being unnecessarily exposed to the potential dangers of dangerous weather conditions or other aviation-related risks.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Crew and patient safety is the single most important factor to be considered when deciding whether to transport a patient by helicopter.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Weather, air traffic patterns, and distances (such as from the trauma scene to closest level 1 trauma centre) must also be considered.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Another reason for cancelling a flight is based on the comfort of the flight crew with the flight.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some have questioned the safety of air medical services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] While the number of crashes may be increasing, the number of programs and use of services has also increased.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Factors associated with fatal crashes of medical transport helicopters include flying at night and during bad weather, and postcrash fires.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] An **air ambulance** is a specially outfitted helicopter or fixed-wing aircraft that transports injured or sick people in a medical emergency or over distances or terrain impractical for a conventional ground ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Fixed-wing aircraft are also more often used to move patients over long distances and for repatriation from foreign countries.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] These and related operations are called *aeromedical*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some circumstances, the same aircraft may be used to search for missing or wanted people.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Like ground ambulances, air ambulances are equipped with medical equipment vital to monitoring and treating injured or ill patients.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Common equipment for air ambulances includes medications, ventilators, ECGs and monitoring units, CPR equipment, and stretchers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A medically staffed and equipped air ambulance provides medical care in flight—while a non-medically equipped and staffed aircraft simply transports patients without care in flight.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Military organizations and NATO refer to the former as *medical evacuation (MEDEVAC)* and to the latter as *casualty evacuation (CASEVAC)*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air traffic control grants special treatment to air ambulance operations, much like a ground ambulance using lights and a siren, only when they are actively operating with a patient.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] When this happens, air ambulance aircraft take the call sign MEDEVAC (formerly LIFEGUARD) and receive priority handling in the air and on the ground.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Most historians believe the first true medical transport mission took place during World War I when a Serbian officer was flown in a French Air Service plane from the battlefield to the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] French records during World War I reported that the air ambulance cut the mortality rate of injured soldiers from 60% to 10%.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The first official recorded air ambulance mission was in 1917 in Turkey when a British ambulance transported a soldier who had been shot to a hospital in 45 minutes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] As with many Emergency Medical Service (EMS) innovations, treating patients in flight originated in the military.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The concept of using aircraft as ambulances is almost as old as powered flight itself.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Although balloons were not used to evacuate wounded soldiers at the Siege of Paris in 1870, air evacuation was experimented with during the First World War.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The first recorded British ambulance flight took place in 1917 in Ottoman Empire when a soldier in the Camel Corps who had been shot in the ankle was flown to hospital in a de Havilland DH9 in 45 minutes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The same journey by land would have taken some 3 days to complete.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the 1920s several services, both official and unofficial, started up in various parts of the world.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Aircraft were still primitive at the time, with limited capabilities, and the effort received mixed reviews.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Exploration of the idea continued, and France and the United Kingdom used fully organized air ambulance services during the African and Middle Eastern Colonial Wars of the 1920s.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 1920, the British, while suppressing the "Mad Mullah" in Somaliland, used an Airco DH.9A fitted out as an air ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] It carried a single stretcher under a fairing behind the pilot.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The French evacuated over 7,000 casualties during that period.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] By 1936, an organized military air ambulance service evacuated wounded from the Spanish Civil War for medical treatment in Nazi Germany.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This service continued during the Second World War.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The first use of medevac with helicopters was the evacuation of three British pilot combat casualties by a US Army Sikorsky R-4 in Burma during WW2, and the first dedicated use of helicopters by U.S. forces occurred during the Korean War, between 1950 and 1953.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The French used light helicopters in the First Indochina War.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] While popularly depicted as simply removing casualties from the battlefield (which they did), helicopters in the Korean War also moved critical patients to hospital ships after initial emergency treatment in field hospitals.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Knowledge and expertise of use of air ambulances evolved parallel to the aircraft themselves.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] By 1969, in Vietnam, the use of specially trained medical corpsmen and helicopter air ambulances led U.S. researchers to determine that servicemen wounded in battle had better rates of survival than motorists injured on California freeways.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This inspired the first experiments with the use of civilian paramedics in the world.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The US military recently employed UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters to provide air ambulance service during the Iraq War to military personnel and civilians.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The use of military aircraft as battlefield ambulances continues to grow and develop today in a variety of countries, as does the use of fixed-wing aircraft for long-distance travel, including repatriation of the wounded.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Currently, a NATO working group is investigating unpiloted aerial vehicles (UAVs) for casualty evacuation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The first civilian uses of aircraft as ambulances were probably incidental.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In northern Canada, Australia, and in Scandinavian countries, remote, sparsely populated settlements are often inaccessible by road for months at a time, or even year-round.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some places in Scandinavia, particularly in Norway, the primary means of transportation between communities is by boat.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Early in aviation history, many of these communities began to rely on civilian "bush" pilots, who fly small aircraft and transport supplies, mail, and visiting doctors or nurses.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Bush pilots probably performed the first civilian air ambulance trips, albeit on an ad hoc basis—but clearly, a need for these services existed.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the early 1920s, Sweden established a standing air ambulance system, as did Siam (Thailand).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 1928 the first formal, full-time air ambulance service was established in the Australian outback.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This organization became the Royal Flying Doctor Service and still operates.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 1934, Marie Marvingt established Africa's first civil air ambulance service, in Morocco.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 1936, air ambulance services were established as part of the Highlands and Islands Medical Service to serve more remote areas of Highland Scotland.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air ambulances quickly established their usefulness in remote locations, but their role in developed areas developed more slowly.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] After World War II, the Saskatchewan government in Regina, Saskatchewan, Canada, established the first civilian air ambulance in North America.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The Saskatchewan government had to consider remote communities and great distances in providing health care to its citizens.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The Saskatchewan Air Ambulance service continues to be active as of 2023.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Walter Schaefer founded the first air ambulance service in the U.S., in 1947, in Los Angeles.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The Schaefer Air Service operated as part of Schaefer Ambulance Service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Two research programs were implemented in the U.S. to assess the impact of medical helicopters on mortality and morbidity in the civilian arena.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Project CARESOM was established in Mississippi in 1969.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Three helicopters were purchased through a federal grant and located strategically in the north, central, and southern areas of the state.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Upon termination of the grant, the program was considered a success and each of the three communities were given the opportunity to continue the helicopter operation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Only the one located in Hattiesburg, Mississippi did so, and it was therefore established as the first civilian air medical program in the United States.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The second program, the Military Assistance to Safety and Traffic (MAST) system, was established in Fort Sam Houston in San Antonio in 1969.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This was an experiment by the Department of Transportation to study the feasibility of using military helicopters to augment existing civilian emergency medical services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] These programs were highly successful at establishing the need for such services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The remaining challenge was in how such services could be operated most cost-effectively.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In many cases, as agencies, branches, and departments of the civilian governments began to operate aircraft for other purposes, these aircraft were frequently pressed into service to provide cost-effective air support to the evolving Emergency Medical Services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] As the concept was proven, dedicated civilian air ambulances began to appear.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] On November 1, 1970, the first permanent civil air ambulance helicopter, *Christoph 1*, entered service at the Hospital of Harlaching, Munich, Germany.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The apparent success of *Christoph 1* led to a quick expansion of the concept across Germany, with *Christoph 10* entering service in 1975, *Christoph 20* in 1981, and *Christoph 51* in 1989.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] As of 2007, there are about 80 helicopters named after Saint Christopher, like *Christoph Europa 5* (also serving Denmark), *Christoph Brandenburg* or *Christoph Murnau am Staffelsee*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Austria adopted the German system in 1983 when *Christophorus 1* entered service at Innsbruck.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Also in the year 1975 Hans Burghart, one of the inventor of the civilian air rescue in Germany, presented at one Academic conference in the US the concept "Rescue Helicopters in Primary and Secondary Missions" which had impact for the aviation training at Fort Rucker, Alabama.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The first civilian, hospital-based medical helicopter program in the United States began operation in 1972.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Flight For Life Colorado began with a single Alouette III helicopter, based at St.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Anthony Central Hospital in Denver, Colorado.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In Ontario, Canada, the air ambulance program began in 1977, and featured a paramedic-based system of care, with the presence of physicians or nurses being relatively unusual.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The system, operated by the Ontario Ministry of Health, began with a single rotor-wing aircraft based in Toronto.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] An important difference in the Ontario program involved the emphasis of service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] "On scene" calls were taken, although less commonly, and a great deal of the initial emphasis of the program was on the interfacility transfer of critical care patients.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Operating today through a private contractor (ORNGE), the system operates 33 aircraft stationed at 26 bases across the province, performing both interfacility transfers and on-scene responses in support of ground-based EMS.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Today, across the world, the presence of civilian air ambulances has become commonplace and is seen as a much-needed support for ground-based EMS systems.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In other countries of Europe, like SFR Yugoslavia, first air ambulance appeared in the 1980s.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Most of the fleet was previously used in military service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] With the increased number of car accidents in 1979 on highways, the Yugoslavian government made a decision to buy new or redistribution of use of old helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air ambulance service, sometimes called Aeromedical Evacuation or simply Medevac, is provided by a variety of different sources in different places in the world.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] There are a number of reasonable methods of differentiating types of air ambulance services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] These include military/civilian models and services that are government-funded, fee-for-service, donated by a business enterprise, or funded by public donations.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] It may also be reasonable to differentiate between dedicated aircraft and those with multiple purposes and roles.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Finally, it is reasonable to differentiate by the type of aircraft used, including rotary-wing, fixed-wing, or very large aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The military role in civilian air ambulance operations is described in the History section.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Each of the remaining models is explored separately.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This information applies to air ambulance systems performing emergency service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In almost all jurisdictions, private aircraft charter companies provide non-emergency air ambulance service on a fee-for-service basis.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some cases, governments provide air ambulance services, either directly or via a negotiated contract with a commercial service provider, such as an aircraft charter company.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Such services may focus on critical care patient transport, support ground-based EMS on scenes, or may perform a combination of these roles.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In almost all cases, the government provides guidelines to hospitals and EMS systems to control operating costs—and may specify operating procedures in some level of detail to limit potential liability.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] However, the government almost always takes a 'hands-off' approach to the actual running of the system, relying instead on local managers with subject matter (physicians and aviation executives) expertise.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Ontario's ORNGE program and the Polish Lotnicze Pogotowie Ratunkowe (LPR) are examples of this type of operating system.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The Polish LPR is a national system covering the entire country and funded by the government through the Ministry of Health but run independently, there is no independent HEMS operator in Poland.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In Northeast Ohio, including Cleveland, the Cuyahoga County-owned MetroHealth Medical Center uses its Metro Life Flight to transport patients to Metro's level I trauma and burn unit.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] There are 5 helicopters for Northeast Ohio and, in addition, Metro Life Flight has one fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the United Kingdom, the Scottish Ambulance Service operates two helicopters and two fixed-wing aircraft twenty-four hours per day.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some jurisdictions, cost is a major consideration, and the presence of dedicated air ambulances is simply not practical.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In these cases, the aircraft may be operated by another government or quasi-government agency and made available to EMS for air ambulance service when required.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In southern New South Wales, Australia, the helicopter that responds as an air ambulance is actually operated by the local hydroelectric utility, with the New South Wales Ambulance Service providing paramedics and doctors, as required.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some cases, local EMS provides the flight paramedic to the aircraft operator as-needed.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the case of the Los Angeles County Fire Department, the helicopters are brush fire choppers also configured as air ambulances with a paramedic provided from whichever fire department rescue unit has responded.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Sometimes the air ambulance may be run as a dual concern with another governmental body - for example, the Wiltshire Air Ambulance was run as a joint Ambulance Service and police unit until 2014.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In other cases, the paramedic staffs the aircraft full-time, but has a dual function.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the case of the Maryland State Police, for example, the flight paramedic is a serving State Trooper whose job is to act as the Observer Officer on a police helicopter when not required for medical emergencies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In many cases, local jurisdictions do not charge for air ambulance service, particularly for emergency calls.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] However, the cost of providing air ambulance services is considerable and many, including government-run operations, charge for service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Organizations such as service aircraft charter companies, hospitals, and some private-for-profit EMS systems generally charge for service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Within the European Union, almost all air ambulance service is on a fee-for-service basis, except for systems that operate by private subscription.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Many jurisdictions have a mix of operation types.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Fee-for-service operators are generally responsible for their own organization but may have to meet government licensing requirements.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Rega of Switzerland is an example of such a service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some cases, a local business or even a multi-national company may choose to fund local air ambulance service as a goodwill or public relations gesture.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In Australia and New Zealand, many air ambulance helicopter operations are sponsored by the Westpac.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In these cases, the operation may vary but is the result of a carefully negotiated agreement between government, EMS, hospitals, and the donor.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In most cases, while the sponsor receives advertising exposure in exchange for funding, they take a 'hands-off' approach to daily operations, relying instead on subject matter specialists.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some cases, air ambulance services may be provided by means of voluntary charitable fundraising, as opposed to government funding, or they may receive limited government subsidy to supplement local donations.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some countries, such as the U.K., use a mix of such systems.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In Scotland, the parliament has voted to fund air ambulance service directly, through the Scottish Ambulance Service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In England and Wales, however, the service is funded on a charitable basis via a number of local charities for each region covered.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Great strides have been made in the UK, with the 'Association of Air Ambulance (AAA)'.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This organization is widely credited for having created the political climate that made the helicopter industry and National Health Service recognise the enormous contribution charities make to trauma care in the United Kingdom.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 2013, the AAA published the "Framework for a High Performing Air Ambulance Service" which details many of the developments from 2008 to 2013.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In recent years, the service has moved towards the physician-paramedic model of care.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This has necessitated some charities commissioning clinical governance services, however many air ambulances operate under the tasking ambulances services clinical governance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The AAA now publishes Best Practice Guidance on a range of operational and clinical functions and provides a code of conduct that all full members, both ambulance services and charities must uphold.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Memorial Hermann Life Flight is a not-for-profit hospital-based critical care air ambulance service in Houston, Texas, USA.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] As of 2023, it operates six EC-145 twin-engine helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The service relies on community support and fundraising efforts.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Memorial Hermann Life Flight operates from the John S.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Dunn Helistop, one of the busiest helipads in the world, with space for four helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A final area of distinction is the operation of large, generally fixed-wing air ambulances.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the past, the infrequency of civilian demand for such a service confined such operations to the military, which requires them to support overseas combat operations.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Military organizations capable of this type of specialized operation include the United States Air Force, the German *Luftwaffe*, and the British Royal Air Force.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The Swedish National Air Medevac - SNAM is an exception to the military only rule where the system is owned by the Swedish Civil Contingencies Agency *Myndigheten för samhällsskydd och beredskap* and the 737-800 aircraft is provided under contract when so required by Scandinavian Airlines.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Each operates aircraft staffed by physicians, nurses, and corpsmen/technicians, and each can provide long-distance transport with full medical support to dozens of patients simultaneously.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] However, in recent years, exceptions to the "military-only" rule have grown with the need to quickly transport patients to facilities that provide higher levels of care or to repatriate individuals.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air medical companies use both large and small fixed-wing aircraft configured to provide levels of care that can be found in trauma centres for individuals who subscribe to their own health insurance or affiliated travel insurance and protection plans.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In most jurisdictions, air ambulance pilots must have a great deal of experience in piloting their aircraft because the conditions of air ambulance flights are often more challenging than regular non-emergency flight services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The resulting CAMTS accreditation, which applies only in the United States, includes the requirement for an air ambulance company to own and operate its own aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some air ambulance companies, realizing it is virtually impossible to have the correct medicalized aircraft for every mission, instead charter aircraft based on the mission-specific requirements.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] While in principle CAMTS accreditation is voluntary, a number of government jurisdictions require companies providing medical transportation services to have CAMTS accreditation to be licensed to operate.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This is an increasing trend as state health services agencies address the issues surrounding the safety of emergency medical services flights.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some examples are the states of Colorado, New Jersey, New Mexico, Utah, and Washington.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] According to the rationale used to justify the state of Washington's adoption of the accreditation requirements, requiring accreditation of air ambulance services provides assurance that the service meets national public safety standards.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The accreditation is done by professionals who are qualified to determine air ambulance safety.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In addition, compliance with accreditation standards is checked on a continual basis by the accrediting organization.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Accreditation standards are periodically revised to reflect the dynamic, changing environment of medical transport, with considerable input from all disciplines of the medical profession.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Other U.S. states require either CAMTS accreditation *or* a demonstrated equivalent, such as Rhode Island, and Texas, which has adopted CAMTS' Accreditation Standards (Sixth Edition, October 2004) as its own.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In Texas, an operator not wishing to become CAMTS accredited must submit to an equivalent survey by state auditors who are CAMTS-trained.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Virginia and Oklahoma have also adopted CAMTS accreditation standards as their state licensing standards.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] While the original intent of CAMTS was to provide an American standard, air ambulance services in a number of other countries, including three in Canada and one in South Africa, have voluntarily submitted themselves to CAMTS accreditation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the UK, the AAA has a Code of Conduct that binds one of the most regulated areas of operation together.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] It brings the Fundraising Standards Board, CAA / EASA and the CQC together ensuring fundraising, air and clinical operations are in line with national regulation and best practice.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The code goes further with an expectation of mutual support and working within its policy and best practice guides.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The nature of the air operation frequently determines the type of medical control required.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In most cases, an air ambulance staffer is considerably more skilled than a typical paramedic, so medical control permits them to exercise more medical decision-making latitude.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Assessment skills tend to be considerably higher, and, particularly on inter-facility transfers, permit the inclusion of functions such as reading x-rays and interpretation of lab results.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] This allows for planning, consultation with supervising physicians, and issuing contingency orders in case they are required during flight.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some systems operate almost entirely off-line, using protocols for almost all procedures and only resorting to on-line medical control when protocols have been exhausted.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some air ambulance operations have full-time, on-site medical directors with pertinent backgrounds (e.g., emergency medicine); others have medical directors who are only available by pager.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] For those systems operating on the Franco-German model, the physician is almost always physically present, and medical control is not an issue.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Most aircraft used as air ambulances, with the exception of charter aircraft and some military aircraft, are equipped for advanced life support and have interiors that reflect this.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The challenges in most air ambulance operations, particularly those involving helicopters, are the high ambient noise levels and limited amounts of working space, both of which create significant issues for the provision of ongoing care.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] While equipment tends to be high-level and very conveniently grouped, it may not be possible to perform some assessment procedures, such as chest auscultation, while in flight.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some types of aircraft, the aircraft's design means that the entire patient is not physically accessible in flight.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Additional issues occur with respect to pressurization of the aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Not all aircraft used as air ambulances in all jurisdictions have pressurized cabins and those that do typically tend to be pressurized to only 10,000 feet above sea level.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] These pressure changes require advanced knowledge by flight staff with respect to the specifics of aviation medicine, including changes in physiology and the behaviour of gases.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] There are a large variety of helicopter makes that are used for the civilian HEMS models.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The commonly used types are the Bell 206, 407, and 429, Eurocopter AS350, BK117, EC130, EC135, EC145, and the Agusta Westland 109, 169 & 139, MD Explorer and Sikorsky S-76.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Fixed-wing aircraft varieties commonly include the Learjet 35 and 36, Learjet 31, King Air 90, King Air 200, Pilatus PC-12 & PC-24, and Piper Cheyenne.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Due to the configuration of the medical crew and patient compartments, these aircraft are normally configured to only transport one patient but some can be configured to transport two patients if so needed.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Additionally, helicopters have stricter weather minimums that they can operate in and commonly do not fly at altitudes over 10,000 feet above sea level.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Beginning in the 1990s, the number of air ambulance crashes in the United States, mostly involving helicopters, began to climb.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] By 2005, this number had reached a record high.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Crash rates from 2000 to 2005 more than doubled the previous five year's rates.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] As a result, nearly fifty percent of all EMS personnel deaths in the United States occur in air ambulance crashes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In 2006, the United States National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) concluded that many air ambulances crashes were avoidable, eventually leading to the improvement of government standards and CAMTS accreditation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Whilst some air ambulances do have effective methods of funding, in England, they remain almost entirely charity funded, as improved cost-benefit ratios are generally achieved with land-based attendance and transfers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Health outcomes, for example from London's Helicopter Emergency Medical Service, remain uncertain.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Although cost-effectiveness may be a consideration in some contexts, in the United States, the primary measure of effectiveness is patient outcomes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Improvements in ground ambulance prehospital care have created uncertainty as to whether helicopter emergency medical services transport is associated with better patient outcomes compared with ground transportation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A U.S. study using 2014 data found that after adjusting for age, Injury Severity Score, and gender, trauma patients who were transferred by helicopter were 57.0% less likely to die than those transferred by ground ambulance (95% CI 0.41 to 0.44, p<0.0001).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A retrospective review study reached a similar conclusion: "Patients transported by helicopter to an urban trauma centre ... had improved survival than those arriving by other means of transport." Patient survival is not the only possible measure of patient outcome.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the case of stroke patients, for instance, various outcome measures could be used.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] There are many considerations in determining whether to dispatch air medical services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Availability, distance and flight conditions are primary considerations.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Even when available, an air ambulance is not always the faster choice in comparison to ground ambulances.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Ground ambulances are more numerous and more ubiquitous, so will often be closer to the scene.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Ground ambulances can depart their base almost immediately, while air medical services must complete preflight routines prior to departure.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A nearby suitable landing site may not be available due to trees, wires, etc.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Air medical services tend to have an advantage where ground access routes to the hospital are congested and for locations more distant from hospitals.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In some situations, it may be desirable to dispatch a ground ambulance that can arrive on the scene first to provide immediate patient care, and an air ambulance to transport the patient(s) to a trauma center.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] It also should be borne in mind that faster may not always be better.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] In the United States, insurance coverage may be a factor.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] For example, the Coverage Policy Manual for Arkansas Blue Cross BlueShield, a not-for-profit mutual insurance company, specifies the circumstances in which costs for air medical services are covered.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The medical personnel of a helicopter ambulance has historically been a Physician/Nurse combination, Paramedic/Nurse, or a Nurse/Nurse combination.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] The need for a Physician/Nurse combination has diminished with more protocol and evidence-based applications for care by nurses and other clinicians and so the inclusion of respiratory therapists in all modes of air transport is becoming more prominent.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Civilian flight nurses may work for hospitals, federal, state, and local governments, private medical evacuation firms, fire departments or other agencies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] They have training and medical direction that allows them to operate with a broader scope of practice and more autonomy than many other nurses.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Some states require that flight nurses must also have paramedic or EMT certification to respond to pre-hospital scenes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Other responsibilities include planning and preparing for aeromedical evacuation missions and preparing a patient positioning plan to facilitate patient care, comfort and safety.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Flight nurses evaluate individual patient's in-flight needs and request appropriate medications, supplies and equipment, providing continuing nursing care from originating to destination facility.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] They act as liaison between medical and operational aircrews and support personnel to promote patient comfort and to expedite the mission, and also initiate emergency treatment for in-flight medical emergencies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] A **transport therapist** is a highly trained respiratory practitioner (also called a respiratory therapist), typically utilized in long-distance transport situations, though able to provide care during shorter transfer.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/air-ambulance] Transport therapists may obtain Adult Critical Care Specialist (ACCS), Neonatal Transport Specialist (NPT) and Neonatal Pediatric Specialist (NPS) certifications from the National Board for Respiratory Care.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel was launched on 2 November 1936 under the name **BBC Television Service**, which was the world's first regular television service with a high level of image resolution.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It was renamed **BBC Television** in 1960 and used this name until the launch of the second BBC channel, BBC Two, in 1964.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The main channel then became known as **BBC1.** The channel adopted the current spelling of BBC One in 1997.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel's annual budget for 2024–2025 was £1.28 billion.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It is funded by the television licence fee together with the BBC's other domestic television stations and shows uninterrupted programming without commercial advertising.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The television channel had the highest reach share of any broadcaster in the United Kingdom as at 2019, ahead of its traditional rival for ratings leadership ITV.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2013, a study conducted across 14 countries by the polling organisation Populus found BBC One to be the station most favourably viewed by its country, with BBC Two coming in third place.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One is available via most major television providers in the United Kingdom.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC began its own regular television programming from the basement of Broadcasting House, London, on 22 August 1932.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel officially began regular broadcasts on 2 November 1936 at three o'clock in the afternoon from a converted wing of the Alexandra Palace in London.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Initially, programmes ran from three o'clock to four o'clock in the afternoon and nine o'clock to ten o'clock in the evening.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Television director Gerald Cock described his rationale for the timings of the service as to "avoid eye strain" for home viewers in breaks between programmes, and to have a five-hour break between both periods in order not to interfere with home routines, such as mealtimes and children's bedtimes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC also depended on newsreels from other companies as it did not have a television news service of its own until 1948.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC Television returned on 7 June 1946 at three o'clock in the afternoon.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Jasmine Bligh, one of the original announcers, made the first announcement, saying, "Good afternoon everybody.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Twenty minutes later, BBC Television again aired the Mickey Mouse cartoon that they had broadcast in 1939.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It carried the 1948 Summer Olympics, which tested the limits of new television equipment, the most ambitious outside broadcast that the BBC had ever done to date.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel was made available outside of London for the first time on 17 December 1949, when the Sutton Coldfield transmitting station in the Midlands opened.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC hoped for the service to reach 70% of the British population by 1952, then 80% by 1954.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC made its first cross-country broadcast on 27 August 1950, crossing the English Channel in cooperation with its French counterpart RTF in Calais, lasting for one hour.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] From this experiment, the term "Eurovision" was coined, which was later adopted by the European Broadcasting Union as the name of its network, which in 1954 was already fully operational.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC held a statutory monopoly on television broadcasting in the United Kingdom until Associated-Rediffusion, the first Independent Television (ITV) station, began to broadcast on 22 September 1955.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Lord Reith, which had long left his position at the corporation, compared its introduction to a plague at the House of Lords.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] While Reith's predictions did not come to pass, BBC Television's viewing share fell down to less than 30% by the end of the decade.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The competition quickly forced the channel to change its identity and priorities, following a large reduction in its audience, as noted in the 1962 Pilkington Report on the future of broadcasting.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Simultaneously, the Pilkington Report decided to award an additional television station to the BBC on the basis that ITV was in comparison lacking in serious programming.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC Television became BBC1 when BBC2 launched on 20 April 1964, transmitting an incompatible 625-line image on UHF.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The only way to receive all channels was to use a complex "dual-standard" 405- and 625-line receiver with both a VHF and a UHF aerial (405-line-only sets became obsolete in 1985 when VHF transmissions ended).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC1 moved to purpose-built facilities at Television Centre on 20 September 1969.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Television News continued to use Alexandra Palace as its base and by early 1968 had even converted one of its studios to colour.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In the weeks leading up to 15 November 1969, BBC1 unofficially transmitted the occasional programme in its new colour system in order to test it.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] At midnight on 15 November, simultaneously with ITV and two years after BBC2 had done so, BBC1 officially began 625-line PAL colour programming on UHF with a broadcast of a concert by Petula Clark.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Colour transmissions could be received in monochrome via monochrome 625-line sets until the end of analogue broadcasting.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Competition tactics with ITV flared up again in the early 1970s, when the channel opted to air its key sitcoms at 7:30 pm, countering *Coronation Street* (at the time airing two nights a week) and related drama series.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] During the early years of BBC2, some programmes made for the channel were repeated on BBC1, attracting higher attention there, such as *The Forsyte Saga* when it gained a repeat on this channel.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Between 1973 and 1977, BBC1 achieved an average audience share of 45% under Bryan Cowgill.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This was the channel's most successful period in terms of audience share.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 30 December 1980, the BBC announced plans to introduce a new breakfast television service to compete with TV-am.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] They stated that the new show would be broadcast before TV-am but included the caveat that the new show would not launch until at least November 1981, whereupon new licence fee income could finance the necessary extension of broadcasting hours.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 17 January 1983, one year after originally planned, the first edition of *Breakfast Time* was shown on BBC1, becoming the first UK wide breakfast television service and continued to lead in the ratings until 1984.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 1984, Bill Cotton become managing director of Television at the BBC, and set about overhauling BBC1, which had been slated with poor home grown shows, its heavy reliance on US imports, with *Dallas* and *The Thorn Birds* being BBC1's highest rated programmes and ratings being over 20% behind ITV.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Cotton recruited Michael Grade to become Controller of BBC1 from 1 September 1984 the first time the corporation had recruited someone outside of the BBC, replacing Alan Hart.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The first major overhaul was to axe the unpopular *Sixty Minutes* current affairs programme: this was a replacement for the news and magazine show *Nationwide*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Its replacement was the *BBC Six O'Clock News*, a straight news programme in a bid to shore up its failing early evening slot.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It was believed the BBC were planning to cut short the evening news and move more light entertainment programming in from the 18:20 slot, but this was dismissed.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The Miss Great Britain contest was dropped, being described as verging on the too offensive after the January 1985 contest, with *World's Strongest Man* and *International Superstar* also being cancelled.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC1 was relaunched on 18 February 1985 with a new look, new programming including *Wogan* and *EastEnders*, and a revised schedule to help streamline and maintain viewers throughout the course of the evening.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Grade started to gear most programmes to either on the hour or half past the hour, while *Panorama* and *Omnibus* were both moved after the *Nine O'Clock News*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Grade was also determined to end the dated and inept BBC1 scheduling which was hampering the channel and holding back good programmes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Grade said "When I took over BBC1, I discovered there were wonderful things, it was just a case of where to put them." *Wogan* had been scheduled for a 10 pm slot, but Grade moved it to a 7 pm slot as he believed the show had potential.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] From February to August 1985, a high number of American mini-series were broadcast while filming took place of a number of new home grown programmes, including *'Allo 'Allo!*, *In Sickness and in Health*, and *Open All Hours*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Further improvement came about when the corporation strengthened its drama output costing £30 million, with eight new series, including *Howards' Way*, *All Creatures Great and Small*, *Hold the Back Page*, and *Bluebill*, along with the return of *Bergerac* and *Big Deal*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The increase in the drama department was achieved by switching the money away from the administrative service over a three-year period, after BBC1 was criticised for failing to match ITV's output in drama.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *EastEnders* was moved to a 19:30 slot, where it managed to soar to 20 million, helping the BBC1 audience share increase to nearly 50% for the first time since 1982.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 27 February 1985, *Doctor Who* was placed on an 18-month hiatus.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC originally planned to axe the series as they wished to spend its budgets on new programming for the channel, but was forced to back down from public pressure and *Doctor Who* returned in September 1986.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] At the time Michael Grade and Jonathan Powell were blamed for the decision (Grade was the target of death threats).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 9 September 1985, the long-standing children's programming block was overhauled and rebranded as *Children's BBC*, which gave it dedicated idents for the first time and had a live in-vision presenter, similar to rival ITV's Children's ITV block which had been running since January 1983.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Previously the BBC had broadcast children's programming using BBC1's team of regular duty announcers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The launch presenter for this block, and thus the first Children's BBC presenter of the current format, was Phillip Schofield.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 23 May 1986, long-running lunchtime magazine show *Pebble Mill at One* was broadcast for the last time after being on air for 14 years.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 27 October 1986, BBC1 launched its daytime television schedules.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] During this time, both commercial analogue broadcasters, ITV and Channel 4 had officially begun stereo transmissions using the BBC-developed NICAM system.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Widescreen programming was introduced on digital platforms in 1998.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] For the first 50 years of its existence, with the exception of films and programmes purchased from the United States and elsewhere, almost all the channel's output were produced by the BBC's in-house production departments.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This changed following the passing of the Broadcasting Act 1990, which required that 25% of the BBC's television output be out-sourced to independent production companies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] By 2004, many popular BBC One shows were made for the channel by independents, but the in-house production departments continued to contribute heavily to the schedule.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In December 1991 *Wogan* was to be cancelled, due to falling ratings against a number of ITV shows, in which *Wogan* only managed six million viewers compared to double that for *This Is Your Life*, *The Krypton Factor* and *The $64,000 Question*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Additionally an extra £40 million a year was spent on narrowing the gap on ITV's ratings lead, since a few months prior to this the channel had been criticised for its Autumn schedule, having tired formats, uninspiring scheduling of new programmes and poor scripts.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *Wogan* was replaced with *Eldorado*, in early July 1992, but this was itself cancelled a year later.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *Lois & Clark: The New Adventures of Superman* included in the Saturday night line up to increase variety.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Following the public disapproval of filling its schedule with 25% of repeats during the summer months of 1993, BBC1 agreed to broadcast an extra 110 hours worth of original programming over the same period during the summer in 1994, which included giving *EastEnders* an additional episode per week.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Efficiency savings of £25 million were found and redeployed to the new productions.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The savings were seen as a vindication for Producer Choice, the controversial internal market introduced in April 1993.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] By March 1999, the channel admitted defeat in its ratings war with ITV, with its spring line up emphasising more on serious factual and educational programmes, and drama.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This change in strategy came about after continuing complaints that the channel was appealing to the lowest common denominator to increase viewership.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Reliance on docusoaps and the dropping of the vilified *Noel's House Party* were chastened by the hoax guests on *The Vanessa Show*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Alan Yentob said "The spring package is to remind people of what the BBC is here for, range and ambition you won't find anywhere else at peak time".
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Lorraine Heggessey became Controller of BBC One, a post she took up on 1 November 2000.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] She had previously been sounded out about the job in 1997 following Michael Jackson's departure, but had turned down the opportunity as she felt she was then not yet experienced enough.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] During Heggessey's five years in charge, BBC One's audience share fell by 19.9%, to 23%, although this was in the context of declining audience figures across all British television channels due to increased competition from multichannel digital television.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] However, in 2001 BBC One overtook its main rival ITV in terms of annual audience share for the first time since the rival channel had launched in 1955, although much of this was down to the success of the channel's daytime television line-up, which had its own Controller: Jane Lush.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The moving of *Panorama* attracted criticism that BBC One was sidelining serious programming in favour of more populist output.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Heggessey publicly defended the decision, despite it not being hers, claiming that *Panorama*'s ratings would have "dwindled" in its previous slot.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Heggessey and the BBC's Controller of Drama Commissioning, Jane Tranter, took advantage of the weekday 21:00 slot opening up by moving the news to commission new popular drama output, such as the successful *Waking the Dead* (2000–2011) and *Spooks* (2002–2011).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Immediately after her arrival, Heggessey ordered a review of the "Balloon" idents the channel had been using for its between-programme idents since 1997.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In her opinion, the balloon was "slow and distant" and so, on 29 March 2002, after much speculation, she decided to abandon the "Balloon" idents (and the traditional "Globe" idents the channel had used in a variety of forms since 1963).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] They were replaced by a new style of on-air identity for the channel, the "Rhythm & Movement" idents.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The new idents attracted criticism for going against the traditions of the channel and pandering to "political correctness", as they featured activities performed by people of various ethnicities.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The abandonment of a station clock, and perceived lack of a 'serious ident', also put the BBC in an embarrassing situation just one day into the new look with the death of the Queen Mother.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] One of Heggessey's most notable decisions and last major success at the channel was the recommissioning of the science-fiction drama series *Doctor Who*, which had been a popular hit in previous decades but ceased production in 1989.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Heggessey and Jane Tranter recommissioned the series in September 2003, after Heggessey had spent two years persuading the BBC's commercial arm, BBC Worldwide, to abandon their attempts to make a feature film version of the programme and allow it to instead return it to BBC One.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Heggessey did later concede in a 2005 interview with *The Independent* newspaper that arts programming had suffered a cutback under her control of BBC One.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] However, she did respond to this omission following criticism from the Board of Governors of the BBC by commissioning programmes such as the arts documentary series *Imagine...* (2003–present) and *A Picture of Britain* (2005).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 14 February 2005 it was announced that Lorraine Heggessey was to leave the BBC to take up the post of Chief Executive at production company Talkback Thames.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Five months after her departure, BBC One was named "Channel of the Year" at the Edinburgh Television Festival, primarily on the strength of Heggessey's commissions such as *Strictly Come Dancing* and *Doctor Who*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] His first full year in charge of the channel saw a year-on-year growth in the audience share, with a rise from 22.2% in August 2005 to 23.6% in August 2006.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] However, *Davina* was a critical and ratings disaster, which Fincham subsequently admitted was personally his fault, although he defended the strategy of experimenting with the BBC One schedule.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Fincham later found himself having to publicly defend the £18 million salary that the BBC paid Jonathan Ross in 2006, although Ross's BBC One work—primarily consisting of *Friday Night with Jonathan Ross*—formed only part of his overall BBC commitment.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel was named *Channel of the Year* at the 2007 Broadcast Awards.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Following its rebrand in March 2002, BBC One launched *The One to Watch* campaign, during which animated blocks created the word "The" and moved into the BBC logo.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Each new campaign incorporating the theme retained the same animated sequence.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In May 2007, Fincham decided to drop *Neighbours*, an Australian soap opera, from BBC One after 21 years on the channel, when its producers, FremantleMedia significantly raised the price they wanted the BBC to pay for it in a bidding war.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Fincham commented that it was 'a big loss', but that BBC One would not pay 'the best part of £300 million'.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *Neighbours* left the channel after the BBC's contract to show the programme ended on 8 February 2008, and moved to Channel 5 on 11 February 2008.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *The Weakest Link* was moved from BBC Two to fill the gap, with the afternoon CBBC slot moving 20 minutes earlier.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] There was further controversy in July 2007 when Fincham was accused of misleading BBC One viewers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The incident involved a clip from forthcoming documentary *A Year with the Queen* which was shown to journalists during a press conference.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Fincham admitted the error, but rejected calls that he should resign from his position as a result.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] His future was deemed uncertain following critical comments from Sir Michael Lyons, Chairman of the BBC Trust, and he resigned on 5 October 2007.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2009, a report published by the BBC Trust found scheduling changes had led to a decrease in viewers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This was especially noticeable for *Blue Peter* and *Newsround*, two of CBBC's flagship programmes; *Blue Peter* which recorded its lowest viewing numbers since it started in 1958, and *Newsround* with fewer than 100,000 viewers compared to 225,000 in 2007.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] As part of the Delivering Quality First proposals submitted by the BBC in October 2011 and approved by the BBC Trust in May 2012, all children's programming on BBC One and Two would be moved permanently to the CBBC and CBeebies channels following the digital switchover.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The move was criticised by *Teletubbies* co-creator Anne Wood, who described the changes as "ghettoising children's programmes" and believe it was merely a cost-cutting measure.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Wood said "On the one hand it is inevitable.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] There is a certain amount of overlooking of the fact that children's programmes do get a wider audience than people are aware of ...
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] I have frequently had letters from older people who have enjoyed my programmes as much as children do.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2012, the BBC out-bid ITV for the rights to air a *British* version of Dutch TV talent show *The Voice*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC paid £22 million for the rights to broadcast the show in the UK for two years.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *The Voice UK* achieved good ratings for the BBC but ratings dropped towards the end of the first series and the second series.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2013, *The Voice UK* was rescheduled to avoid a clash, and as a result, ratings have improved.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In November 2015, it was announced that *The Voice UK* would be moving to ITV from 2017, especially because of the ITV plc ownership of franchise owner, Talpa Media.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 8 October 2013, the BBC announced plans to launch a one-hour time shift of the channel, named BBC One +1.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel would have replaced BBC Three in 2016.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] However, on 30 June 2015, the BBC Trust rejected the plans for a BBC One +1 channel as they stated that it would be at the expense of commercial rivals.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One HD at launch did not offer regional variations, and therefore the channel could not broadcast during regional programming slots, most noticeably the local news programmes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC Trust admitted that this was due to technical and financial constraints, but the BBC announced on 6 June 2011 that the national variations of BBC One Northern Ireland, BBC One Scotland and BBC One Wales, would become available from 2012.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 24 October 2012, Northern Ireland received the first variation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] A Scottish variation launched on 14 January 2013, followed by a Welsh variation on 29 January 2013.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 16 July 2013, the BBC indicated that it also wants to launch regional variants of BBC One HD across England; however, this would require the approval of the BBC Trust, with a proposal due to be presented within six months.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 18 November 2013, the Northern Irish regional variant of BBC One HD was swapped with the SD channel on Sky's EPG for HD subscribers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This was followed by the Welsh and Scottish variants on 10 December.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 24 March 2014, BBC One Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland HD launched on Freesat, Sky and Virgin Media outside the regions they were originally seen in.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 31 March 2016, BBC One HD in England moved from channel 141 on the Sky electronic programme guide to channel 115, a position vacated by BBC Three, which had been switched to internet-only six weeks earlier.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Changes in Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland were also scheduled but delayed for 'technical reasons' and eventually BBC Two HD was moved to channel 115 in those regions.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 22 November 2022, the BBC announced that BBC One would finally be regionalised on their HD channels.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This move started on Sky Glass, followed by Virgin Cable, and then in the 2023 new year, HD programmes were launched on satellite.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] With the launch of the HD channels, this also meant the closure of the SD channels.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] SD channels were shut on satellite 24 hours after the launch of the HD channel, and were moved up to the Channel 1/Channel 101 slot on the EPG.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Viewers with older standard definition set-top boxes would no longer be able to receive BBC One.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] All BBC satellite channels in standard definition closed on 8 January 2024.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC Alba HD, BBC Red Button 1 HD and BBC Parliament HD also launched on satellite at a similar time.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC and Freesat launched a website with a guide, telling users how to make sure they are upgraded at www.hdsatelliteupgrade.co.uk.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Regional programming began on BBC One HD in certain regions on 22 March 2023; it began in the remaining regions on 26 April 2023, as well as regionalised versions launching on Freeview that same day.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] With a mission to provide programmes for all licence-fee payers, it has sport, news, current affairs, and documentaries.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It has historically broadcast children's programmes (now taken from CBBC and CBeebies).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Since 1990, the BBC has had to commission output from other domestic suppliers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Although the statutory target remains 25% for independent production companies to contribute programming for BBC One, 33% of output was made by them in 2010–11.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The quota of original programming in peak times is set at 90%; however, 100% of peak programming was original in 2010–11.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Over the whole day, the total for the same year was 89%, against a quota of 70%.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] All three main news bulletins have a lead over their rival programmes on ITV and other terrestrial or cable channels.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] During the weekend period, three separate bulletins around these three time periods are broadcast and vary in length from 10 to 25 minutes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One has broadcast overnight simulcasts from the BBC News Channel since 1997; the latter in turn simulcasts the majority of all regular BBC One bulletins.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] When BBC One is broadcasting a BBC News special, it hands some of its daytime programming to BBC Two.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Each year 159 hours of current affairs programmes are broadcast on BBC One, including *Panorama* and *Watchdog*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Politics is also covered, with programmes including *Question Time* and *This Week* shown.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *Crimewatch*, a programme appealing for help in unsolved crimes, is broadcast monthly.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One shows 1,880 hours of factual and learning programming annually.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This includes a wide range of shows such as nature documentaries such as *Planet Earth* as well as lifestyle-format daytime programmes and a number of *reality television* formats and the *One Life* strand.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One broadcasts 1,036 hours of drama each year, more than any other BBC channel.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] There are four half-hour episodes of *EastEnders* each week (not shown on Friday), plus the hospital drama *Casualty*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Other popular dramas on BBC One include crime dramas such as *New Tricks*, a programme of which even episode repeats have beaten ITV ratings on numerous occasions.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One has traditionally been the home of children's television: *Blue Peter* had been broadcast on the channel prior to the Children's BBC strand, and sections such as the pre-school *Watch with Mother* being transmitted on the channel for several decades.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This became more pronounced with the launch of Children's BBC, later renamed "CBBC".
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This new strand was broadcast primarily on BBC One in the late afternoons, as well as Saturday and Sunday mornings also such as *Going Live!* and *Live & Kicking*, each lasting two to three hours.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The launch in 2002 of dedicated digital channels for this content —the CBBC and CBeebies channels —did not affect this provision.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Combined with BBC Two, the channel broadcast 2,195 hours of children's programmes in 2010, mostly in the late afternoons on weekdays.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Saturday morning children's programming moved to BBC Two in 2006 following a three-month trial.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Sports coverage on BBC One includes Premier League football highlights on *Match of the Day*, the Wimbledon Championships, the London Marathon, and other international athletics and swimming events, the Olympic Games, Rugby league, Rugby Union, Snooker tournaments, the American Super Bowl, and more.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC showed the 2010 FIFA World Cup, splitting the group stage matches with ITV.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC had first pick of matches from the second round.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Programming on this channel costs an average of £162,900 per hour.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] British and international films are broadcast for 654 hours each year on BBC One.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This is mainly late-night fillers with some box office hits at Christmas and holiday periods.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Sometimes on a Saturday afternoon there is a film on to fill the gap between entertainment shows but very rarely has there been one in that slot.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Entertainment programming on BBC One includes game shows such as the *National Lottery*, *Total Wipeout*, *Strictly Come Dancing* and chat shows such as *The Graham Norton Show*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The annual 92 hours of religious programming comprise weekly editions of live *Songs of Praise*, Christian services and other shows from independent production companies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Mentorn Oxford produces *Heart and Soul*, described as "a new multi-faith programme featuring a panel and a studio audience", followed by *Life from the Loft* which is made by the Leeds-based company True North.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2005 BBC One was criticised for reducing the amount of religious programming, previously 101 hours per year.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One broadcasts many comedy programmes, often on Friday nights.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] These have included the stand-up comedy show *Live at the Apollo*, sitcom *Outnumbered*, and satirical quiz show *Have I Got News for You*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Saturday evening is also a popular slot for a comedy show such as *Michael McIntyre's Big Show* and *The Armstrong and Miller Show*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Since BBC Three became an online-only service in 2016, BBC One broadcast some BBC Three programming, particularly such as *People Just Do Nothing*, *Cuckoo*, *RuPaul's Drag Race UK* and *This Country*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In March 2019, BBC1 had a dedicated timeslot for BBC3 as a programming block.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The block was dropped when BBC Three returned as a linear TV channel in early 2022, but BBC One continues to broadcast some BBC Three programmes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] As the weekly popular music chart programme *Top of the Pops* was dropped in 2006 (except for the Christmas Day edition), BBC One broadcast 49 hours of music and arts programming in 2010.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The majority of this was *Imagine*, presented by Alan Yentob, and classical music concerts, in particular some of the *BBC Proms*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One's daytime line-up was a major factor in it overtaking ITV as the most popular channel in 2000, a position it has retained, even though ITV achieves a higher audience share during the daytime.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The morning daytime line-up consists of lifestyle shows, such as *Morning Live*, *Homes Under the Hammer* and *Bargain Hunt*, the afternoons contain drama with daily soap *Doctors* and classic US drama, such as *Diagnosis: Murder*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Sometimes a drama such as *Land Girls* is shown in the afternoons.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Between 15:25 and 17:35 was the CBeebies/CBBC broadcasting strand, with its own visual identity.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Historically, BBC One's most popular daytime programme was *Neighbours*, with audience figures approaching five million.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 11 February 2008, BBC One dropped *Neighbours* and the programme was broadcast on Channel 5 until 2022.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In its place was the quiz show *The Weakest Link*, which was moved from BBC Two, and later replaced in 2011 by *Pointless*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Children's programmes were broadcast from 15:05 - 17:15 to accommodate this change and this continued until December 2012 when the afternoon CBeebies/CBBC block was axed.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 16 May 2012, the BBC announced the children's block of shows would be moved permanently to CBBC and CBeebies upon the completion of the Digital switchover.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In its place appear the game show *Perfection*, plus *Escape to the Country* and *Put Your Money Where Your Mouth Is*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In February 2022, the BBC confirmed that *EastEnders* will get a Monday to Thursday slot at 7:30 pm with the programme due to form part of a BBC soap hour which will include a repeat of daytime soap *Doctors* on BBC Two at 7 pm.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Due to this decision, the BBC One regional slot will be pushed back half an hour to 8 pm on Wednesdays, where it will feature programmes such as documentary series *We Are England*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One's identity has been symbolised by a globe shown on its idents for much of its existence.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The first BBC ident was shown on 2 December 1953, known as the Bat's Wings.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 1962 this was replaced by a map of the UK shown between programmes, and in 1963 the globe appeared, changing in style and appearance over the next 39 years.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Most notably, on 18 February 1985, the "Computer Originated World" was introduced.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This was a computer-animated globe with the land coloured gold and the sea a transparent blue, giving the impression of a glass globe.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] This was replaced by the "Virtual Globe" on 16 February 1991.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 4 October 1997, the globe became a red, orange and yellow hot-air balloon, coloured to resemble a globe.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] It was filmed flying around various places in the UK.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 29 March 2002, the globe was replaced by a series of visual identities, "idents", consisting of people dancing in various styles.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] These were replaced on 7 October 2006 by the 'circle' idents.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] According to the BBC, the circle symbol both represents togetherness (unity) and acts as a link to the classic globe icon used for 39 years.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] They ran until 4 December 2016, when that year's Christmas idents launched.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 1 January 2017, a new ident set launched, based on the theme of "oneness".
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The idents were reinstated on 19 July 2021 when the UK government lifted some Coronavirus restrictions until the new Lens idents arrived the following year on 1 April 2022.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One is not one unified channel, but has several different feeds that form a television network.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One has individual continuity and opt-outs for Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] Each variant maintains the BBC One logo with the addition of the constituent country name beneath it.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In England, each region has an individual regional news and current affairs programme opt-out as well as a limited amount of continuity.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] *UK Today*, a news programme, was shown nationally to digital viewers in place of regional programmes when they were unavailable to broadcast on analogue television.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The programme was discontinued in 2002 and replaced by a transmission of *BBC London News* until all BBC regions were made available digitally.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One Scotland has the greatest level of variation from the generic channel, owing to BBC Scotland scheduling Scottish programming on the main BBC Scotland channel, rather than on BBC Two Scotland which closed in 2019.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One Scotland variations include the soap opera *River City* and the football programme *Sportscene*, the inclusion of which causes programming to be displaced or replaced.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One Wales was considered a separate channel by the BBC as early as its launch in the mid-1960s, appearing as BBC Wales.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One (Northern Ireland) is widely available in Ireland on cable and satellite television.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] BBC One (especially the London feed) is also available on cable and IPTV in the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, Monaco and Liechtenstein.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The channel is registered to broadcast within the European Union/EEA through the Luxembourgish Broadcasting Regulator – ALIA.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] On 27 March 2013 it was offered by British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS) to members of HM Forces and their families around the world, replacing the BFBS 1 TV channel, which already carried a selection of BBC One programmes.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] All feeds of BBC One in both SD and HD are broadcast unencrypted on the Astra 2E and 2G satellites, allowing viewing across Belgium, the Netherlands, the Republic of Ireland and parts of France, Germany and Spain.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC announced in May 2008 that it had achieved its aim for all programming to have subtitles for viewers with hearing difficulties.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The BBC also offers audio description on some popular BBC One programmes for visually impaired viewers.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] The percentage of the BBC's total television output with audio description available is 10%, having been increased from 8% in 2008.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bbc-one] In 2016, the controller of BBC One would be promoted to oversee all BBC channels, with the channel controller roles being entirely scrapped in 2020, in favour of a focus on digital streaming.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital has its origins in the **Hospital for Sick Children** on St Michael's Hill founded in 1866.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The initial building was a large converted dwelling house on Royal Fort Road, south of the Royal Fort gatehouse, with accommodation for 40 patients.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the hospital's first salaried doctors was the pioneering female surgeon, Eliza Walker, appointed as House Surgeon in 1873.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] A much expanded hospital was built nearby to the designs of Robert Carwen in the Tudor gothic revival style in 1885.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Only the entrance building fronting on to St Michael's Hill now survives.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital was later renamed as the **Bristol Royal Hospital for Sick Children**.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The new Children's Hospital opened on 22 April 2001, replacing the old children's hospital on St Michael's Hill, at a cost £30 million.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the main aims of the design, in addition to providing the most up-to-date facilities possible, was to overcome many of the difficulties that face patients, families and staff.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In February 2014, it was agreed an inquiry would be held into the Bristol heart scandal, following heart surgery deaths at the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The inquiry published a report in June 2016, saying that “parents had been let down”.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] An extension was built to accommodate services moved from Frenchay Hospital in 2014, including neuroscience, scoliosis surgery, burns and plastic surgery, bringing all inpatient children's services in Bristol to one location.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2015, a neuro-rehabilitation unit was built to support the moved services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In May 2014, a new helipad on the roof of the neighbouring Bristol Royal Infirmary became fully operational and will receive air ambulances from Bristol and the surrounding area, which will speed up transfer times for patients who are air lifted to the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The HELP Appeal supported the construction of the helipad with a grant of £500,000.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal is the only charity that fundraises exclusively for the hospital and the neonatal intensive care unit at St Michael's Hospital, to provide facilities and comforts for patients and their families.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal raised £12M towards the new building for the child-friendly hospital, which opened in April 2001.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Sculptures were decorated by a range of artists and celebrities, including Joanna Lumley, Sir Peter Blake, Cath Kidston and Jools Holland.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] At the end of the art trail, each sculpture was auctioned to raise funds for Bristol Children's Hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal has pledged to raise £3.5M for equipment for Bristol Children's Hospital, including a state of the art CT Scanner, an intraoperative MRI scanner, family facilities and child-friendly artwork to help save the lives of sick children at the hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] All funds raised by Gromit Unleashed will contribute towards this.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Bristol & Weston Hospitals Charity (BWHC) raises around £2M for all ten hospitals in the trust.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It provides equipment, ward refurbishments and additional extras.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It was formerly known as Above & Beyond and has existed since 1974.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2013, the charity's Golden Gift Appeal raised £6M.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 1997, arts consultant, Lesley Greene, was commissioned to develop an arts strategy for the new hospital.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] This project was committed to integrated designs, a commitment to consultation and the family.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Her active research programme led to the appointment of lead artist, Ray Smith, Eva Elsner, and Annie Lovejoy who contributed to the planning of the commissions programme.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Artworks were commissioned from more than twenty artists, many of which were site specific.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] These commissions were funded by the hospital's own fundraising arm, The Wallace and Gromit Grand Appeal.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Records of the Bristol Royal Hospital for Children are held at Bristol Archives (Ref.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] 37424) (online catalogue) and School of Nursing records (Ref.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow Helicopters was established by Alan Bristow in June 1955; two years later, it acquired its first pair of helicopters in the form of the Westland Widgeon.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The company quickly expanded overseas as well as various services, including helicopter training, oil exploration, search and rescue, and charter flights.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Having entered the African market in 1960, Nigeria became Bristow's biggest profit centre during the 1970s.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Entering the North Sea market, also during the 1960s, Bristow became Aberdeen Airport's largest single employer during the 1980s and was operating the majority of offshore flights in the North Sea.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The company went through repeated changes in ownership during the 1980s and 1990s, leading to its acquisition by American helicopter operator Offshore Logistics in 1996, which re-branded itself as **Bristow Group** in February 2006.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow Helicopters Limited holds a United Kingdom Civil Aviation Authority Type A Operating Licence, it is permitted to carry passengers, cargo and mail on aircraft with 20 seats or more.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The U.S. division of Bristow is a Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) approved Part 135 air carrier.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] On 11 May 2019, Bristow Group entered Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, affecting North America operations, but leaving overseas operations unchanged.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] After an aggressive expansion earlier in the decade, demand was cut back as crude oil prices dropped and Bristow Group's total debt stood at $1.44 billion by 30 September 2018.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow completed the UK's Eastern Airways sale on 10 May, and still wants to sell its interest in Australia's Airnorth, hoping for $230 million combined.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1960, Bristow Helicopters chose to enter the African market via the acquisition of crop-spraying specialist *Fison-Airwork*, which had also operated in locations in Central America and the UK.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow opted to discontinue crop-spraying activities in favour of focusing on oil exploration work in Nigeria on behalf of Shell; by the start of the Biafran War in 1967, the company had a fleet of 11 helicopters committed the Nigerian oil exploration effort, based at Port Harcourt.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Early on in the conflict, Bristow helped to evacuate oil workers in the region to the safety of Fernando Po; despite the risks, Bristow maintained its Nigerian operations throughout the three years of war via a reduced presence in Lagos and Warri.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] This decision to remain gave the company a head-start on rivals as oil companies returned to the region after the war's end.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Throughout much of 1970s, Nigeria functioned as Bristow's biggest profit centre; it continued to grow through the decade via contracts from Shell, Mobil, Texaco and other companies.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In the mid-1960s, Bristow opted to enter the North Sea market; being the second helicopter operator (after BEA Helicopters Limited) to establish operations at Aberdeen, Scotland, it was relatively well positioned to take advantage of the region's oil boom.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Starting on 17 February 1965, the company operated the Westland Wessex 60 ten-seat helicopter to support these off-shore installations.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Throughout the 1970s, Bristow would expand its Aberdeen operation, its main oil and gas support hub being based at Dyce Airport; in 1972, the company allocated the first of several Sikorsky S-61N to Sumburgh Airport in support of Shell's offshore rigs.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Following an expansion programme, which included the building of new on-site accommodations for workers and their families, around thirty S-61N flights were routinely flying daily from Sumburgh, supported by round-the-clock maintenance coverage, at the peak of operations during the 1970s.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] During the 1980s, Bristow became Aberdeen Airport's largest single employer, its personnel in Aberdeen having increased a hundred-fold, as well as operating the majority of offshore flights in the North Sea.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1980 alone, nearly 400,000 passengers and over 2,300 tons of freight passed through Bristow's Aberdeen terminal.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] By 1970, Bristow had also established a training joint venture in Iran, although this was discontinued after the Iranian Revolution of 1979.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] During the late 1960s, Bristow Helicopters operated a fleet of Hiller UH-12 training helicopters based at AAC Middle Wallop which were used to train flight crews on behalf of the UK Army Air Corps.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1986, the company began training overseas pilots at its flying school at Redhill Aerodrome; this program ran for multiple decades, being rebranded as the *Bristow Academy*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In addition to pilot training, Bristow has also been involved in training ground crew, having started sponsoring students at the Nigerian College of Aviation Technology, (NCAT), Zaria, in 1986.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Starting in 1971, Bristow Helicopters began providing civilian search and rescue (SAR) services in the UK, replacing military Westland Whirlwinds with Bristow-operated Sikorsky S-55s at RAF Manston, Kent.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The then-unfamiliar concept of using a private company for SAR services led to a public outcry and intense lobbying efforts thus, after three years, operations were turned back over to RAF Coastal Command.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow reentered the UK's SAR sector in 1983 when it commenced operations on behalf of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) from Sumburgh Airport; the company held the contract until 2007 and secured it again in June 2013.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Other locations, including Stornoway, Lee-on-Solent, and Portland, would also be operated by Bristow on behalf of MCA.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Over the years, Bristow's SAR units have responded to multiple incidents, including rescue efforts in the recovery of survivors of the Piper Alpha disaster.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] During the early 1970s, the backbone of Bristow's fleet consisted of the Westland Wessex, Westland Whirlwind, and Bell 206, along with a handful of other types, including several fixed-wing Britten-Norman BN-2 Islanders.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] By the 1980s, Bristow had entirely phased out the Wessexes; the bulk of its fleet came to consist of Bell 206s, Bell 212s, and Sikorsky S-76s, amongst other types, during this period.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow was in fact the first European operator to adopt the Sikorsky S-76 into commercial service.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The company also played a leading role in the development of the Aérospatiale Super Puma, having consulted with Aerospatiale to shape its design for the oil and gas market, branding it "Tiger" rather than "Super Puma" for its own fleet.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow decided to place a larger order for 35 Super Pumas, or "Tigers", this being the largest civil helicopter order to have been made at the time; the first examples of the type were introduced in early 1982.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The business had also developed a worldwide presence within a similar timeframe, providing its services in the North Sea, Middle East, South America, Africa, Asia, India, Bermuda, Trinidad, Australia and New Zealand.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The company went through repeated changes in ownership during the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1985, Bristow Helicopters was acquired by British and Commonwealth Holdings plc.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] That same year, Alan Bristow stood down from his active role in managing the company.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] It was soon sold on as a component of the Bricom Group via a management buy-out in 1988.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In July 1990, Bricom was acquired by Scandinavian investment company Rochfield.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1991, Bristow Helicopters was subject to another management buy-out headed by managing director and chief executive Bryan Collins.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In 1996, Bristow Helicopters was purchased by *Offshore Logistics*, an American offshore helicopter operator which previously operated as *Air Logistics* in the U.S.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Gulf of Mexico and Alaska, and was structured as a reverse takeover.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The group operates and maintains a global fleet of over 400 aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In February 2006, Offshore Logistics decided to re-brand itself as *The Bristow Group*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In January 2010, Bristow announced the retirement of the Air Logistics name and Gulf of Mexico operations would operate under the name Bristow.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The Bristow Group expanded their portfolio in April 2007 with the purchase of Helicopter Adventures, a Florida-based flight school, Helicopter Adventures was subsequently renamed *Bristow Academy*.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The deal also provided the Bristow Group with the world's largest civilian fleet of Schweizer aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In January 2019 it was announced that Bristow would acquire Columbia Helicopters for $560 million.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The deal was later cancelled and Bristow paid Columbia a $20 million termination fee.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] It was announced in April 2022 that Bristow Group was to acquire British International Helicopters in an all cash transaction.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The sale was completed on 2 August 2022.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The purchase included all of BIH's aircraft, employees and existing contracts.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The BIH name and branding will be phased out and replaced by that of the wider Bristow Group.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In addition to its wholly owned international operations, Bristow Group maintains service agreements and equity interests in helicopter operators in Brazil, Canada, Colombia, Egypt, Kazakhstan, Turkmenistan, Mexico, Norway and Russia (Sakhalin) and the United Kingdom.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] This allows Bristow to extend its range of services into new and developing oil and gas markets and helps provide a lower cost structure in some operating areas.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Fixed Wing Bristow has controlling interests in Eastern Airways which is a regional airline based in the U.K. operating fixed wing regional jet and turboprop aircraft and Airnorth, also a regional airline, based in Australia operating fixed wing regional jet and turboprop aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Both Eastern Airways and Airnorth operate scheduled passenger services, shuttle flights for oil and gas industry personnel, and charter services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Although not a joint venture, in 2015 Bristow and AgustaWestland agreed to develop offshore and search and rescue capabilities for the AW609 tiltrotor.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] This could simplify a typical trip from Clapham Common to an oil rig by using just one aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow intends to order more than 10 tiltrotors.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow helicopters operated Sikorsky S-61N helicopters on behalf of HM Coastguard, the United Kingdom's coastguard, until July 2007 after which there was a 12-month transitional period whilst CHC Helicopter took over the contract replacing the S-61N with new helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow operated four dedicated Search and Rescue (SAR) sites in the UK, on behalf of HM Coastguard.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] The units were located at Portland (EGDP) and Lee-on-Solent (EGHF) on the south coast of England, at Stornoway (EGPO) in the Outer Hebrides, and at Sumburgh (EGPB) in the Shetland Isles.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Northern North Sea services operated from Aberdeen (EGPD), Scatsta (EGPM) and Stavanger (ENZV).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Southern North Sea services operate from Norwich (EGSH), Humberside (EGNJ) and Den Helder (EHKD) with its support organisation based at Redhill (EGKR).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow S-61N's were responsible to carry out SAR tasks, operating from Den Helder Airport on behalf of the oil and gas industry.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] On 26 March 2013, Bristow was awarded a 10-year contract to operate the search and rescue operations in the United Kingdom, at the time being provided by CHC Helicopter (on behalf of HM Coastguard), the Royal Air Force and the Royal Navy.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow is currently operating AgustaWestland AW139, AgustaWestland AW189 and Sikorsky S-92 helicopters in support of this contract.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] As part of its acquisition of British International Helicopters, Bristow also operates support as well as search and rescue helicopters out of RAF Mount Pleasant in the Falkland Islands.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Two Sikorsky S-92 helicopters are used for everyday military transport and land logistic support around the islands, where there are few roads and a 12-mile (19 km) strip of sea separates the two main islands.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Search and rescue is conducted using two AW189 helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] In July 2022 it was announced that Bristow had been awarded a second ten-year contract.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow operates a large fleet of over 450 helicopters and aircraft, which includes unconsolidated affiliates and joint venture partners.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] Bristow intends to reduce fleet variety from 24 helicopter types to six.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/bristow-helicopters] For subsidiary Airnorth fixed wing jet and turboprop aircraft, see Airnorth.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] The **Children's Acute Transport Service** (CATS) is a publicly funded specialised regional intensive care transport service for critically ill children.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the busiest Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Service in the UK and covers the 50 District General Hospitals in the North Thames and East Anglia regions of England.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is part of the Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Only a proportion of hospitals have a Paediatric Intensive Care Unit PICU.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Therefore, most critically ill children initially present to hospitals without a PICU.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Paediatric Intensive Care Transport Services are designed to provide the safe and rapid transfer of these children to a regional PICU.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS was created in 2001 as a collaborative service for the North Thames Regional PICU's: The Royal Brompton Hospital, St Mary's Hospital, London and Great Ormond Street Hospital for Children.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS receives ~2200 referral calls and performs ~1200 critical care retrievals each year.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Over 75% of these children are too unwell to breathe for themselves and require anaesthesia and a ventilator.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] A third need inotropic (inotrope) support, and about 5% require inhaled nitric oxide during transport.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Telephone advice, liaison with sub-specialist medical services and outreach education are also important parts of the service's activity.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Service Level Agreements (SLA) exist with Great Ormond Street Hospital and the Freeman Hospital in Newcastle for ECMO (extracorporeal membrane oxygenation) retrievals.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS also provide a paediatric intensive care transport service with Great Ormond Street Hospital for retrieval of children with Vein of Galen malformations requiring radiological ablation.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] 5-10% of retrievals are performed by air ambulance.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] This is via both helicopter and fixed-wing aircraft.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] For many of these urgent long distance transfers, the team works with the aircraft and the crews of HM Coastguard helicopters.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS have moved many paediatric patients internationally.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS has received accreditation from the Commission on Accreditation of Medical Transport Systems (CAMTS).
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] This independent, non-profit agency audits medical transport services against industry-established criteria.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS accreditation is for fixed-wing and rotary wing air medical transport services as well as ground inter-facility critical care services.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Department of Health, Health and Social Care Award, National Winners 2005.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] NHS intensive care consultants are responsible for service delivery, supervision of junior medical staff, provision of outreach education and service development.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] All full-time CATS consultant intensivists, cover sessions in PICU/anaesthesia to maintain competencies in their base speciality.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of full-time CATS nurses is responsible for service delivery, co-ordination of the outreach education program, and in-house training.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] In addition, over 50 nurses rotate from each of the 3 PICUs to cover the rota.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] A team of administrators provide 24-hour cover for the Referral Hotline and co-ordinate incoming referrals, teleconferencing and communication with clinical team members.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] Road ambulance retrievals are provided by St John Ambulance using bespoke CATS designed intensive care ambulances.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] CATS is the subject of an eight-part (8 x 30 minute) series called Children's Emergency, produced by September Films for BBC One.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-acute-transport-service] It aired between 4 May and 23 June 2010.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-emergency] Eight episodes were produced by September Films for the BBC, and it was first aired on BBC One between 4 May and 23 June 2010.
[src:children-s-acute-transport-service/children-s-emergency] The documentary depicts the life-saving work of the medics with real live footage, as they deal with a wide range of critical conditions in their little patients, such as brain infections, lung and heart failure, car accidents, blocked intestines and diabetes with coma.
